  "text": "Reflecting the strong instrumentality in much existing research, associations between difficulty and intended learning outcomes are common. Outcomes are understood to reflect alignment between difficulty in the form of required acuity, and opportunity to engage in authentic situations. Learning outcomes of simulation depend on flow and plausibility, enabling students to suspend disbelief and perform in a realistic manner [CITATION_1] ). Flow and plausibility imply that the simulation hits a particular level of difficulty governed by realism (too easy or too hard, and it feels unrealistic). But also implied here is the notion that stepping into the simulated world as if real can itself be a source of difficulty. These authors note that psychological challenges can trigger emotional engagement and aid the process of immersion in the 'as-if' world of simulation.",
